                                                                   425 1451
 GENERAL COMMENTS                                                  425 1451
    The neutron energy range covered extends from .00001 eV to     425 1451
 20 MeV. In addition to elastic scattering which of course is      425 1451
 everywhere energetically possible, the following reactions have   425 1451
 thresholds at energies less than 20 MeV [Ho1970]:                 425 1451
                                                                   425 1451
              reaction               threshold (mev)               425 1451
              n,2n                    1.85                         425 1451
              n,p                    14.26                         425 1451
              n,np                   18.76                         425 1451
              n,d                    16.29                         425 1451
              n,nd                   18.55                         425 1451
              n,t                    11.60                         425 1451
              n,nt                   19.65                         425 1451
              n,alpha                 0.67                         425 1451
              n,n alpha               2.74                         425 1451
              n,gamma                exoergic                      425 1451
                                                                   425 1451
    For the (n,np), (n,nd), and (n,nt) reactions, there are no     425 1451
 measurements and since the thresholds are sufficiently high,      425 1451
 these cross sections are assumed to be negligible. The            425 1451
 (n,n alpha) reaction is a decay mode for the (n,2n) reaction      425 1451
 since 5He is unstable, decaying immediately to a neutron and an   425 1451
 alpha particle.  The inelastic scattering reaction is also a      425 1451
 decay mode for the (n,2n) reaction since the 9Be* recoil nucleus  425 1451
 always decays to the final end products of a neutron and two      425 1451
 alpha particles.                                                  425 1451
    The selection of the cross sections for elastic scattering,    425 1451
 (n,2n), (n,p), (n,d), (n,t), (n, alpha), (n, gamma), and the      425 1451
 (n,x gamma) reaction is discussed below.                          425 1451
                                                                   425 1451
 ELASTIC SCATTERING CROSS SECTION                                  425 1451
    The free atom cross section is used for all energies below     425 1451
 the upper limit of the molecular binding energy (about 10 eV).    425 1451
 This is effectively only the nuclear part of the cross section of 425 1451
 a stationary target at zero Kelvin. It is strongly emphasized     425 1451
 that the numbers are meaningless in the absence of a proper       425 1451
 thermal treatment by either the processing code or the neutronics 425 1451
 code which uses these numbers. They are likewise meaningless      425 1451
 if the materials for which they are to be used are bound in       425 1451
 molecules unless molecular binding is taken into account.         425 1451
    The scattering cross section was taken equal to 6.15 barns     425 1451
 [Mu1981] from 0.00001 eV to 0.01 MeV. From .01 MeV to the         425 1451
 (n,alpha) threshold at 0.67 MeV, the elastic scattering cross     425 1451
 section is equal to the total cross section since the (n,gamma)   425 1451
 cross section is negligible.  The cross section was based on      425 1451
 experimental data [63, 92, 720, 772, 1002].                       425 1451
    Above the (n,alpha) threshold, the scattering cross section    425 1451
 was taken as the difference between the total and the nonelastic, 425 1451
 with the nonelastic being equal to the sum of its parts. Up to 2  425 1451
 MeV, the total cross section was based on the previously          425 1451
 mentioned data, and those from [72, 336, 1642].  From 3.2-4.4     425 1451
 MeV, the Argonne total cross section data was used [Sm1988].      425 1451
 From 4.5-10. MeV the Argonne elastic cross section data was used  425 1451
 [Sm1988].  Also above 2. MeV, we relied on the results of Johnson 425 1451
 [3088] over the 2.7 MeV resonance, and Foster [750] and the       425 1451
 elastic scattering data from Hogue [4113] and Drake [4473] up to  425 1451
 15 MeV.  For incident neutron energies from 15 to 20 MeV, the     425 1451
 data from Cook [107], Peterson [673], and Fossan [682] were used. 425 1451
                                                                   425 1451
 ELASTIC SCATTERING ANGULAR DISTRIBUTIONS                          425 1451
   (NORMALIZED PROBABILITIES)                                      425 1451
   Up to 7 MeV, there are experimental differential scattering     425 1451
 data [121, 151, 231, 296, 500, 571, 945, 1643, 1645, 1646, 1647]  425 1451
 which were used to determine the normalized probabilities. Below  425 1451
 the (n,2n) threshold, the total scattering data are equivalent    425 1451
 to those for elastic scattering.  The change in shape of the      425 1451
 angular distribution going through the scattering resonances was  425 1451
 taken into account. From 4.5-10 MeV the Argonne differential      425 1451
 elastic scattering cross sections were used [SM1988].  From 6-15  425 1451
 MeV, the results of [4113, 4473, 402, 2585, 3106] were also       425 1451
 used. A smooth extrapolation was made to 20 MeV.                  425 1451
                                                                   425 1451
 (N,2N)                                                            425 1451
    The evaluation for the 9Be (n,2n) reaction is described in     425 1451
 detail in Perkins [Pe1985].  A Monte Carlo technique was used and 425 1451
 the calculated spectra were compared against recent double        425 1451
 differential cross section measurements.  At each incident        425 1451
 neutron energy, 5,000,000 events were sampled, resulting in       425 1451
 10,000,000 secondary neutrons. The (n,2n) reaction was described  425 1451
 by the following four events:                                     425 1451
         Be9(n,n1)Be9*(n2)Be8*(alpha1)alpha2,                      425 1451
         Be9(n,n1)Be9*(alpha1)He5*(n2)alpha2,                      425 1451
         Be9(n,alpha1)He6*(n1)He5*(n2)alpha2,                      425 1451
         Be9(n,He5*1)He5*2,                                        425 1451
              He5*1(n1)alpha1,                                     425 1451
              He5*2(n2)alpha2.                                     425 1451
 Where, n is neutron, alpha is alpha particle, and * denotes an    425 1451
 excited state. Wide level transitions were considered as          425 1451
 required.                                                         425 1451
                                                                   425 1451
 TOTAL (N,2N) CROSS SECTION                                        425 1451
    The total (n,2n) cross section was based on the data from      425 1451
 [683, 763, 3320, 4473, 4871, 5660].  At 14 MeV, the weighted      425 1451
 mean of the eight values measured between 1958-1963 was also      425 1451
 considered. The resulting curve is similar to that used in        425 1451
 ENDF/B-V.                                                         425 1451
                                                                   425 1451
 (N,2N) DOUBLE DIFFERENTIAL SPECTRA                                425 1451
    The calculated double differential spectra were compared       425 1451
 to 51 measurements between 3.25 and 15.4 MeV:                     425 1451
 [4871] (3.25-15.4 MEV), Drake [4473] (5.9-14.2 MeV), and          425 1451
 Takahashi [Ta1982].  See also [Ta83] (14 MeV).  Comparisons were  425 1451
 made after weighing the calculated results with the experimental  425 1451
 resolution function. The final calculated spectra were then       425 1451
 smoothed and thinned. This yielded double differential spectra    425 1451
 for both the secondary neutrons and the secondary alpha           425 1451
 particles.                                                        425 1451
                                                                   425 1451
 (N,P) CROSS SECTION                                               425 1451
    This cross section is entirely for the (n,p0) reaction and     425 1451
 was based on the data from Alburger [913] and Augustson [3492].   425 1451
 It was smoothly extrapolated from 15.5 to 20 MeV. The proton was  425 1451
 assumed isotropic in its center of mass system.                   425 1451
                                                                   425 1451
 (N,D) CROSS SECTION                                               425 1451
    This cross section is entirely for the (n,d0) reaction and     425 1451
 was based on the data between 15.5 and 19 MeV reported in Scobel  425 1451
 [4841].  The deuteron was assumed isotropic in its center-of-mass 425 1451
 system.                                                           425 1451
                                                                   425 1451
 (N,T) CROSS SECTION                                               425 1451
    The cross section for the (n,t) reaction is based on a         425 1451
 (n,t0) and a(n,t1) component, which proceed through the 0. and    425 1451
 the 0.477 MeV levels in 7Li respectively. The total (n,t) cross   425 1451
 section near 14 mev was determined from [496, 3996, 5722].        425 1451
    The (n,t1) cross section was based on the work in Dietrich     425 1451
 [5529] and smoothly extrapolated from 15 to 20 MeV. The           425 1451
 resonance near threshold is consistent with structure in the      425 1451
 compound system 10Be.                                             425 1451
    Both tritons were assumed isotropic in their center-of-mass    425 1451
 systems.                                                          425 1451
                                                                   425 1451
 (N,ALPHA) CROSS SECTION                                           425 1451
    The cross section was based on the measurements reported       425 1451
 in Stelson [160], Vasilev [494], and Bass [733] up to neutron     425 1451
 energies of 8.6 MeV.  It was then tied into the four values given 425 1451
 at 14 MeV by Battat [86], Myachkova [650], Paic [2367], and       425 1451
 Perroud [Pe1978].  It was then extrapolated to 20 MeV.  Note      425 1451
 that the  measured cross section is to 6He (0. MeV) which beta    425 1451
 decays to 6Li; higher states in 6He decay to alpha + 2n.          425 1451
    The alpha particle angular distribution was taken as isotropic 425 1451
 in the center of mass system at threshold. At 14.1 MeV the data   425 1451
 from the measurement of ref; 4351 was used; this distribution     425 1451
 was also used at 20 MeV.                                          425 1451
                                                                   425 1451
 (N,GAMMA) CROSS SECTION                                           425 1451
    The cross section was assumed to be 1/v below 100 eV with      425 1451
 a 2200 m/sec cross section of 8.6 mb. This is in agreement with   425 1451
 the CSEWG dosimetry and activation files. It was then             425 1451
 extrapolated linearly on a log-log basis to 0.1 mb at 1 keV and   425 1451
 then held constant at this value up to 20 MeV.                    425 1451
                                                                   425 1451
 (N,X GAMMA) CROSS SECTION                                         425 1451
    Gamma rays in 9Be are produced by the (n,gamma) and the (n,t)  425 1451
 reactions.  At thermal energies, Rasmussen [2415] quotes gamma    425 1451
 ray energies of 0.8535, 2.59, 3.368, 3.444, 5.958 and 6.81 MeV    425 1451
 and the corresponding (n,x gamma) cross sections.  The photon     425 1451
 spectrum from this work was used at all neutron energies.         425 1451
    The multiplicity varied with neutron energy as m(e) =          425 1451
 m(0)(e(cm)+Q)/Q, where m(0) is the multiplicity at thermal and    425 1451
 Q is the (n,gamma) Q value.  This combination of spectra and      425 1451
 multiplicity conserves energy.  There are no doubt other levels   425 1451
 in 10Be with energies greater than 6.81 MeV are excited as the    425 1451
 incident neutron energy is increased.  The energies of the higher 425 1451
 states have not yet been determined so we use this artifact to    425 1451
 conserve energy.  The component resulting from the (n,t) reaction 425 1451
 is equal to the (n,t1) cross section since its multiplicity is    425 1451
 unity.                                                            425 1451
